  />

  <Toc
    items={[
      { href: '#quick-answer', label: 'Quick answer' },
      { href: '#what-you-need', label: "What you'll need" },
      { href: '#step-by-step', label: 'Numbered dial-in steps' },
      { href: '#common-mistakes', label: 'Common mistakes' },
      { href: '#faq', label: 'Frequently asked questions' },
    ]}
  />

  <h2 id="quick-answer">Quick answer</h2>
  <p>Start around 18g in and 36g out, then target roughly 25 to 32 seconds as your timing window. If your shot runs fast and tastes sour, move slightly finer. If your shot runs slow and tastes bitter, move slightly coarser. Keep dose and yield fixed while dialing so each grind move is easy to interpret.</p>

  <h2 id="what-you-need">What you'll need</h2>
  <p>You need fresh beans, a scale that reads to 0.1g, a consistent puck prep routine, and a grinder with enough fine-range control for espresso. The more stable your routine, the easier it is to identify whether the grinder setting is truly wrong or if prep drift caused the issue.</p>
  <p>For workflow context, compare our <a href="/posts/best-burr-grinder-for-espresso.html">best burr grinder for espresso</a> roundup and our <a href="/posts/best-hand-grinder-for-espresso-under-100.html">best hand grinder for espresso under $100</a> guide. If your machine is the limiting factor, check <a href="/posts/best-espresso-machine-under-200.html">best espresso machine under $200</a> as well.</p>

