  <h2 id="step-by-step">Numbered steps to dial in burr grinder settings for espresso</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Lock one baseline recipe first</h3>
  <p>Pick a single baseline recipe before touching grind: 18g in, 36g out is a strong starting point for most home espresso setups. Keep water temperature, puck prep, and tamp pressure consistent. When variables stay fixed, grinder changes become meaningful instead of random.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: Pull one reference shot and classify it</h3>
  <p>Run one shot and write down time plus taste. Keep your language simple: sour/fast, balanced, or bitter/slow. That gives immediate direction. Sour and fast usually means finer. Bitter and slow usually means coarser. Resist over-correcting after one imperfect pull.</p>

  <h3>Step 3: Make tiny adjustments and retest</h3>
  <p>On stepped grinders, move one click at a time. On stepless collars, make very small nudges and retest. Big jumps often overshoot and waste beans. As you approach balance, prioritize flavor clarity and sweetness over forcing one exact shot time.</p>

  <h3>Step 4: Save your setting and maintenance cadence</h3>
  <p>Once you land in a good zone, log the setting with bean name and date. Beans degas, humidity shifts, and retention buildup all push extraction around during the week. A short log plus regular cleaning makes your next dial-in faster and more accurate.</p>

  <ProsCons
    pros={[
